  "studyDescription": "In a 1990 Stanford study, 'tappers' tapped out the rhythm of well-known songs (like 'Happy Birthday') on a table, and 'listeners' tried to identify the song. Tappers predicted that 50% of listeners would guess correctly, but only 3 out of 120 listeners (2.5%) identified the song. This study illustrates how people overestimate their ability to communicate \u2014 tappers could 'hear' the song in their heads while tapping, but listeners heard only a disconnected series of taps. This is an observational study.",
  "variableDescriptions": {
    "outcome": "Whether the listener correctly identified the song being tapped (correct or incorrect)."
  },
  "sourceDetail": "Elizabeth Newton (1990), Stanford doctoral dissertation. Summarized in IMS 2e Section 12.1 and Heath & Heath (2007), 'Made to Stick.'",
  "context": {
    "population": "listeners attempting to identify tapped songs",
    "parameter": "proportion who correctly identify the song",
    "nullClaim": "the true proportion of correct identifications equals the tappers' prediction of 50%"
  },
